{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_easton_ver02/data/sn89060127/00279521961/1924012601/0037.xml":{"full_text":"Saturday, January 26, 1924\nBUSINESS POINTERS.\nBuy your Hats at Callahan's.\nBuy our guaranteed Boots at Cal*\nlahan's.\nPure Country Lard at Hillman\u2019s\nMarket.\nDress yourself from head to foot\nat Callahan\u2019s.\nWANTED Hogs at Hillman\u2019s\nMarket.\nIt\u2019s about time you had that picture\ntaken. The right place for good pic\ntures is Harris\u2019 Studio.\nHome made Sausage and Scrapple\nat HILLMAN\u2019S MARKET\nWANTED\u2014IOO men at the Baptist\nChurch every Sunday morning.\nH. B. PILCHARD.\nYou wffll find Pure Mountain Buck\nwheat flour and home ground tabic\nhominy at EAGLE MILLS.\nFOR RENT\u2014Apartment of foui\nrooms. Possession Feb. 1. Apply tc\n612 Market St. 1-5,-tf..\nFOR SALE\u2014AII wool bed blankets.\nsl2 per pair. Apply to\nFRANK E. HUDSON.\nWANTED\u2014Large young chickens.\nAlso eggs. B. F. Sturgis, comer of\nVine street and Clarke avenue. Tele\nphone 119.\nFOR RENT\u2014Three desirable of\nfices in the Woolworth Building. Im\nmediate possession.\nl-5-4t. M. L. VEASEY.\nBring your eggs to us. We pay the\nhighest market cash price.\nAMERICAN STORES COt,\nPocomoke City, Md\nNOTICE\u2014I am prepared to make\nall kinds of fancy pies, at reasonable\nprices.\n1-19-tf. MRS. C. O. HUFFMAN.\nSTORE FOR RENT\u2014January Ist\nNow occupied by American Store.\nFurther information at\nFISHER\u2019S BARGAIN STORE.\nFOR RENT\u2014Rear apartment ovei\nA. H. Stevens store on Market street\nApply to\nJan. 12-tf. A. H. STEVENS\nFOR RENT Desirable apart\nment. Apply to\nE. CARMEL WILSON,\n12-29-tf. 828 Second St.\nEGGS WANTED whites and\nbrowns. Live poultry. Highest cash\nprices paid for same.\nG. H. EVANS.\nNOTICE\u2014 Get your house moved\nby the house mover, who has had .15\nHi experience in moving all size\nings. G. T. Groton. Parksley, Vo\nEggs and Poultry wanted. Don\u2019t\nhold broilers as Market is inclined\nlower. Comer Vine street and Clarke\nave. Phone 119. B. F. STURGIS.\nFOR RENT\u2014Present location of\nCitizens Bank. Will be vacated Feb\nruary Ist. Apply to\nDec. 29. QUINCE ASHBURN..\nWANTED\u2014A middle-aged woman\nfor housekeeping. Experience neces\nsary. Apply to\nMRS. M. I. HEILIG,\n1-19-tf. Clarke Ave.\nConsult the Landscape Gardner a\nbout your garden problems, just ae\nyou do a doctor or a lawyer. Avoid\nmistakes and get results. Interviews\nupon request. Terms reasonable, ac\ncording to service rendered. Emily\nS. Kauffman, R. 1, Westover, Md.\nFOR RENT\u2014Two nicely furnished\nfront rooms. Light, Heat, Bath and\nTelephone. Comer Clarke avenue and\nCedar street.\n1-26 MRS. EVELYNE EVANS.\n\u201cBABY CHlX\u201d\u2014Place orders now\nfor Baby Chix as my hatching space\nis limited, and am booking orders\ndaily. Phone 119 ,comer Vine street\nand Clarke avenue.\nB. F. STURGIS.\nWANTED\u2014Young woman in coun\ntry home to assist light housekeep\ning, and care of invalid woman. Good\nhome and wages to proper party.\nMust give reference. Apply to Demo\ncrat office. Nov-24-tf.\nNOTICE\u2014 Custom hatching and\nday old chicks hatched from our vig\norous strain of S. C. White Leghorns.\nG. G. VON SICK,\nP. O. Westover, Md.\nJan 19, 3t. Costen, Md.\nFOR SALE Farm near Wel\nbOume, containing about 100 acres\nwith 60 to 70 acres well set in pine\ntimber. Will sell as a whole or sepa\nrate. Possession at once. Farm sow\ned in rye.\nDec 29 E. J. REID.\nOyster roasts will continue during\nthe season. Those desiring service\nalong my line can communicate with\nme by phone at Thomas Wharton\u2019s\nstore. B. DISHAROON,\nSep-29-tf. Stockton, Md.\nFOR RENT\u2014Ground floor apart\nment of dwelling on Willow street\nnow occupied as law offices of Ewell\nChild. Possession January 1, 1924.\nApply to\nL. PAUL EWELL,\nAttomey-at-Law,\nPocomoke City, Md.\nFOR SALE\u2014One hundred and thir\nty-two shares Standard Wholesale\nPhosphate and Acjd Works, Inc.\nstock. This is Standard Fertilizer\nCompany\u2019s stock, and its par is S2O\nper share. If interested write\nH. A. NOCK,\n1-19-tf. Onley, Va.\nWill take a limited number of voice\npupils at my home at King\u2019s Creek,\nor will teach a class of ten or more in\nchorus singing in Pocomoke City.\nItalian bel canto method used, which\nis perhaps the best for preserving and\ndeveloping the voice. Phone Princess\nAnno 46-F-3, or address R. F. D., No.\n2, Westover, Md.\nl-19-4t. MRS. IDA CARTER.\nReal Estate Transfers.\nMarde V. Gray and Stewart F.\nGray, her husband, from Harvey T.\ni Pilchard and wife, part of the \u201cGray\nFarm\u201d or the \u201cE. Fillmore Merrill\n5 Farm,\u201d containing 61 acres, 3 roodg\nand 4 perches, more or less, on both\nsides of the \u201cNew Neck Road\u201d leading\nfrom Pocomoke City to Cedar Hall.\nCharles T. Jones and Achsah M.\nJones, his wife, from George H.\nJones and wife and another, 8.35 acres\nof land, more or less, on the south side\nof the County road leading from\nFriendship to Taylorsville, in the 3d\nElection district.\nJesse J. Taylor from Chester M.\nGunby and wife and others, garage\nproperty on the Easterly side of Main\nstreet, together with house and lot\nAdjoining, in Berlin, v\nUrie Hudson from Peter W. Dono\nway and wife, 66 acres of land, more\nor less, on the road leading from Wha\nleyville to Rehoboth Church in the 9th\nElection district.\nCharles R. Hudson from Walter E.\nHudson and Susan A. Haddox, house\nand lot containing 3 Acres, more or\nless, in St. Martin\u2019s Neck.\nFrank H. Sturgis from Paul Stur\ngis and wife, real estate on Martin\nstreet, in Snow Hill.\nElmer H. Showell and Annie Show\nell, his wife, from James R. Bishop,\nSr., 19 acres, 2 roods and 20 perches\nof land, more or less, about 1 mile\nnorthwesterly from Showell, in the\n9th Election district. Consideration,\n$1,250.\nArchie E. Davis from Clifford P.\nGroper and wife and another, lot in\nWest Ocean City, on the north side of\nihe State road leading from Ocean\nGity to Berlin.\nThomas H. Hastings from Clifford\nP. Cropper and wife and another, lot\nin West Ocean City, on the North\n3ide of the State road leading from\nOcean City to Berlin.\nWm. F. Johnson from E. H. John\nson, Trustee, 160 acres of land, more\nor less, on both sides of the County\nroad leading from the Public Landing\n\u2019oad to the Bayside road at Franklin\nschool house site, in the 2nd Election\ndistrict. Consideration, $365.\nJ. Harry Young, Frank D. Young\nand J. Milton Clogg from John J.\nDickerson, real estate on the North\nside of Front street, in Pocomoke\nCity.\nJohn C. F. Borger from Emma A.\nFoster, 2 tracts of land containing 20\nacres, more or less, near Ironshire, in\n;he 9th Election district.\nJoseph E. Shockley from the Selby\nille Bank, 160 acres of marsh land\nadjoining Assawaman Bay and the\nDelaware and Maryland State line, in\nthe 6th Election district. Considera\ntion, SIOOO.\nHoward W. Hastings and Alice C.\nHastings, his wife, from Alfred F.\nPowell and wife, house and lot on the\nSoutheasterly side of Williams street,\nin Berlin.\nJames S. Clogg from L. Paul Ewell,\nAssignee, farm in the First Election\n\"district, on the East side of the State\nstone road leading from Pocomoke\nCity to Snow Hill. Consderation,\n$4,650.\nAnnie K. Griffin from John W.\nStaton and wife and another, part of\nthe \u201cKlee Farm,\u201d containing 10 acAs,\nmore or less, in East Berlin Election\ndistrict.\nBUSINESS POINTERS.\nFOR SALE True Barred Rock\ndggs, 76c per setting of 15, or $4.00\nper hundred. 1-19-tf.\nMRS. W. W. BEAUCHAMP.\nSALESMAN for lubricating oils\nand paints. Excellent opportunity.\nBig returns. JED OIL AND PAINT\nCO., 3701 Burwell Avenue, Cleveland,\nOhio. 1-26-lt\nLOST\u2014One Shepherd puppy-\u2014last\nseen on Clarke avenue, Jan 16. Re\nj ward, if returned to\nJ. F. THORINGTON,\ni l-26-2t. Pocomoke City.\nWANTED Wide awake young\nman with car, to sell in Worcester\ncounty, the Caleb Boggs Son, guar\nanteed true to name line of tomato\nseed, wholesale and retail. Write,\n1 phone or make appointment with ref\nerences for full particulars as to A\ngents Commission. Phones 22 and 78.\nR. O. DEAN,\u2018Distributor\nEastern Shore Maryland and Virginia\nJan-26-2t. Federalsburg, Md.\nGIVARZ STORE NEWS\nf Agency for American Lady Cor\n<ets. There are no better.\nIf in need of a Coat, Sait or Dress,\nvisit our second floor department.\nThe only correct patterns are the\n2 Butterick. We sell them.\nNone better than ready-to-wear in\nladies\u2019 goods than we carry,\ni New arrivals in Coats, Suits, and\nj Dresses. It is the biggest, and best\ng and most reasonable priced line we\nhave ever had. Give us a call.\nBENJAMIN GIVARZ.\nPocomoke City, Md.\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT, POCOMOKE CITY, MARYLAND\nLOCAL AND PERSONAL\nMr. W. B. Sartorius spent the week\nin Norfolk, Va.\nMrs. D. W. Shaw, Jr., is confined tq\nher home on account of illness.\nMr. and Mrs. A. H. Hardesty, of\nBerlin, were visitors in town Sunday.\nMrs. Annie Cluff is visiting her\ndaughter, Mrs. Ira Turner of Salis\nbury.\nMrs. E. F. Taylor, of Hallwod, Va.,\n1 visited her son, Mr. J. S. Chesser last\n1 week.\nMrs. Fred Mapp, of Belle Haven,\nVa., is the guest of Mrs. Frank E.\nHudson.\nMr. F. M. Wilson made a business\ni trip to Baltimore the early part of\nthe week.\nMiss Ethel M. Matthews spent last\nweek-end with relatives and friends in\n1 Onancock, Va.\nMrs. Richmond Picken has been\nvery ill with bronchitis, but is now\nmuch improved.\nMr. Howard Strong, of Chester\ntown, was a caller at the Democrat\u2019s\noffice this week.\nMrs. M. W. Godwin and children\nare spending the week visiting rela\ntives in Virginia.\nMiss Nellie Grice spent the week\nend with her sister, Mrs. McClure, at\nFederalsburg, Md.\nMr. W. B. Duncan has \u2018returned\nfrom Baltimore where he attended the\nAutomobile show.\nMiss Rosaline Stevenson is quite ill\nat the home of her grandmother, Mrs.\nClarence E. Stevenson.\nMr. and Mrs. W. C. Burroughs and\ndaughter, Miss Mary, spent the week\nend with Mr. and Mrs. W. A. Coryell.\nMr. Pletz has been transferred from\nthe Railroad Signal department here\nto Wilmington, Del. Mr. Pletz\u2019s place\nis being Ailed by Mr. Freemon. j\nMr. M. W. Godwin and his assistant\nare spending the week in New York\nbuying spring and summer merchan\ndise for the Godwin Department store, j\nMrs. Jennie Matthews left for Lake\nCity, S. C., last Thursday where she.\nwill visit her daughter, Mrs. L: R.\nTruluck, and her son, Mr. Robert Mat\nthews. j\nIn St. Mary\u2019s Church at 10 A. M.\nSaturday, February 2, there will be;\nHoly Communion in observance of the\nFeast of the Purification of St. Mary,\nthe Virgin.\nHon. E. W.' McMaster attended a\nmeeting of the State Board of Educa\ntion this week in Baltimore; leaving\nhome on Wednesday last and return\ning \"On Saturday.\nMessrs. James Tilghman, Charles\nMarshall, Herman Bozman, and Bryce\nBounds motored to Salisbury, Tues\nday evening, on a skating party.\ni\nMiss Rachael Johnson gave a card\nparty, Saturday evening, at her home\nat New Church, Va. Among the\nguests present were Miss Mae Kellam\nof Painter, Va., and Mr. Granville\nHall of Pocomoke.\nMrs. George P. Fleming, of Ports\nmouth, Va., who came here to attend\nthe funeral of her nephew, Charles O.\nDunton, has returned to her home.\nMrs. Elizabeth Griffin accompanied\nher for a short visit.\nShoes\nGREATLY REDUCED\n500 PAIRS WOMEN\u2019S SHOES\nSELLING FOR $lO, sll, sl2\nAll Reduced to\n$7.95\nAll sizes, but not in every\nnumber. All brand new\nshoes in the latest styles.\nBlack satins, Black suedes,\nGray suedes, and Patent\nLeathers.\nAll reduced because of\nour policy never to carry\nmerchandise from one sea\nson to another. Take advan\ntage of this opportunity.\nAll sales final.\nJ\nHARGIS\nDEPARTMENT STORE\nPOCOMOKE\nSSSSSSSSSSSSSSSSSSSSSiiSSSSSSSS\n1 St. Mary\u2019s Guild will meet Friday\nafternoon, February Ist, at 3 o\u2019clock\nwith Miss Elizabeth Cluff.\nMr. William Shrieves, of Parksley,\nVa., is on a visit to his sister, Mrs.\nMatthews of Fourth street.\nMrs. Edward J. Clarke returned on\nSaturday last from a four weeks\u2019 vis\nit to relatives in Norfolk, Va.\nMiss Marion Stevens, of Delmar,\nspent the week-end with her parents,\nMr. and Mrs. A. H. Stevens.\nRichard Hancock, son of Mr. and\nMrs. D. K. Hancock is recovering\nafter a severe illness of typhoid\nfever.\nThe regular meeting of Crescent\nChapter Eastern Star, will be held on\nMonday night, January 28 at 7.30\no\u2019clock.\nMiss Bertie Benson, of Pitts Creek,\nwho was operated on for appendicitis\nat the Peninsula General Hospital,\nSalisbury, about two weeks ago, re\nturned to this city Thursday, accom\npanied by her mother, Mrs. Addie\nBenson, who for the last three months\nhas been taking treatment there.\no o\nGodwietc\nDEPARTMENT STORE kJ J\nO\nJ POCOMOKE CITY, MD.\n3 PFAere f/te Woman Who Knows Buys Her Clothes\n4 THE MARVEL NON-ELECTRIC VACUUM CLEAN-\n4 ER opens a new channel for clean and more healthful homes. 4\nDust is filth in its most dangerous form., Dust pollutes the 4\nair that we breathe, the food that we eat, the liquids we\ndrink, and the houses in which we live.\nfTHE MARVEL NON-ELECTRIC VACUUM\nCLEANER is replacing the electric cleaners o\ng in many homes, and to those women whose 4 4\nhomes are not electrically wired these Marvel o\nCleaners wijl prove of the highest benefit and 4\nawaken your instant admiration and interest.\nJt will truly be a \u201cMarvel\u201d to you in that\nyou can now get the same results from this\ncleaner without electricity in your home as\nyoilr friends do with electric cleaners. 4\nAlways ready in any home, no wires to get\nin your way, no operating cost, easy and quiet\nto operate. Gathers threads, sand and grit in 4\nany rug. Half the price of an electric and o\nwithin the means of all housewives They are\nsold al lover the wof-ld and guaranteed. Priced\nat $35.00. Terms if (desired. Come in and get\na demonstration or better still, order one on a 44\nweek\u2019s free trial and return it if you don\u2019t\nuiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiliiimiiiiiiiiiiiiiiimit\n11\nJudge a Store by\nWhat It Does\u2014\nNot by what it should do.\nS\nS\n1 In our never-ending efforts to give\nalways something better at a price\na little lower, we have succeeded\n1 in demonstrating on many occa\nsions that we give more than what\nwe promise\u2014-and let the others\npromise more than what they give.\nS s\nVisit our store often and\nget among our customers\nand always remain our\nfriend.\nJ Pocomoke City, Md. 1\n1 mu min\nMrs. Farrel Bowen and son Edward\nFarrel left this week for an extended\nvisit with relatives in Elkton.\nMrs. A. Stengle Marine, of Cam\nbridge, Md., spent Sunday and Mon\nday with Mrs. Emma R. Colboume.\nMaster Ralph Ross, Jr., is ill with\ntonsilitis at his grandmother\u2019s home,\nMrs. Parker Ross, of Market street.\nMr. George L. Seville, of Philadel\nphia, a former resident of this city,\nhas been on a visit to relatives here.\nFrancis Warren left Friday morn\ning for Baltimore where he will visit\nhis sister, Mrs. W. M. Patterson, for\nsome time.\nMrs. Emerson W. Polk left the ear\nly part of the week for Philadelphia\nand Baltimore where she will spend\nthe rest of the winter.\nRev. F. W. Clayton and Rev. George\nV. Bell will exchange pulpits tomor\nrow, Sunday, January 26. The former N\nwill preach in St. Mary\u2019s Church, this\ncity, at 10.30 A. M. The latter will go\nto Princess Anne and officiate in St.\nAndrew\u2019s Church, services at same\nhour.\no\nf- Are You\nReady?\nReading the signs, they plainly indicate that the\nbusiness depression is permanently behind us.\n\n33 Business in general assumes a decidedly more opti\n-3; mistic outlook, and the business man with vision is al\n-3 I ready carefully laying his plans for the business revival\n33 that is upon us.\nj 3 One of the first and most important actions should\n3 3 be your association with the BANK that is in a position\nj 3 to\u2019best serve your requirements from a financial and ad\nvisory standpoint.\n\n33 This bank most cordially invites an interview with\n3 3 any one considering the establishment of new or addi\n-3 I tional banking connections.\nThe Citizens National Bank\nOF POCOMOKE CITY\njt BANK HABIT\nSAVING HABIT\nPROSPERITY\n3 OLD AGE COMFORTS\nt\nII Tried and Approved Plans j:\no 33\njj For 78 years this Company has confined its busi- jj\n;3 ness to tried and approved plans. Its appeal is j j\n33 to those who want pure life insurance with the j\nj 3 most liberal features and at the lowest possible j\ncost. j 3\nThe Mutual Benefit\nLife Insurance Co.\nn o\nI H. M. WALTERS, District Mgr. ji\nX o\nv\no\nij Meeting the Price Issue\nI; squarely with a\n$29.50\nSuit Value that\u2019s astonishing! ii\no\no\n\n33 The store that dodges the issue of low prices also\n33 dodges a lot of good business this month.\n3 3 Men tighten up after the Holidays and it remains 3 3\n3 3 for a store that\u2019s eager for increased business to 3 3\n31 feature low prices that will pry open sealed 3 3\n31 purses.- 3 3\n1 3 This is that type of Value! v 3I\n3 3 So strong that a man needn\u2019t need clothes to buy\n3I two suits right now\u2014this minute.\n33 Come\u2014this is not idle talk\u2014and you won\u2019t find\n3 3 us idle when you come in either.\ni 3 $29.50 FOR THE SUITS\n33 $29.50 FOR THE COATS o\n3 3 Get your appetite whetted for Value and we\u2019ll\n3 3 satisfy you on that score when you get here.\n\n\ni O\nii R. J. Lambden Son ii\n\n33 THE SQUARE DEAL SHOP\n33 POCOMOKE CITY, MD.\nI\nPage 5","height":"23631","width":"19068"}}
